WEBVTT

00:00:00.350 --> 00:00:03.460
<v Narrator>Amazon Lightsail is a bit of an oddball in AWS</v>

00:00:03.460 --> 00:00:06.070
because it is kind of a stand-alone service.

00:00:06.070 --> 00:00:06.920
So with Lightsail,

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:08.120
you can get virtual servers,

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:08.953
storage,

00:00:08.953 --> 00:00:09.786
databases

00:00:09.786 --> 00:00:11.580
and networking in one place.

00:00:11.580 --> 00:00:14.050
It gives you low and predictable pricing.

00:00:14.050 --> 00:00:16.730
And so the reason people use Amazon Lightsail

00:00:16.730 --> 00:00:19.610
is that it is a much simpler alternative

00:00:19.610 --> 00:00:20.940
to using services

00:00:20.940 --> 00:00:21.773
that we've been learning

00:00:21.773 --> 00:00:25.770
such as EC2 RDS, ELB, EBS, Route53 and so on.

00:00:25.770 --> 00:00:28.940
So Lightsail really the intent of it from AWS

00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:31.850
is for people that have little cloud experience

00:00:31.850 --> 00:00:32.930
and don't want to learn

00:00:32.930 --> 00:00:35.950
how the services work intricately,

00:00:35.950 --> 00:00:36.783
for example,

00:00:36.783 --> 00:00:37.730
how their networking works,

00:00:37.730 --> 00:00:38.563
how the storage works,

00:00:38.563 --> 00:00:40.150
the server works etc.

00:00:40.150 --> 00:00:41.340
This is not something you would use

00:00:41.340 --> 00:00:43.300
your learning how AWS works properly

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:44.550
but if you're someone with little

00:00:44.550 --> 00:00:45.920
to no cloud experience

00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:48.360
then Lightsail maybe a service for you.

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:50.650
From Lightsail you can also set up some monitoring

00:00:50.650 --> 00:00:52.940
and notifications for your Lightsail resources

00:00:52.940 --> 00:00:54.570
and so use cases for Lightsail would be

00:00:54.570 --> 00:00:55.403
for example,

00:00:55.403 --> 00:00:58.020
if you want to deploy a very simple web application

00:00:58.020 --> 00:00:58.853
for example,

00:00:58.853 --> 00:01:01.790
if you have LAMP Stack, Nginx, MEAN, Node.js

00:01:01.790 --> 00:01:04.460
there's templates for that on Lightsail

00:01:04.460 --> 00:01:05.760
or if you have a very simple website,

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:06.593
for example,

00:01:06.593 --> 00:01:07.426
if you have a WordPress and Magento,

00:01:07.426 --> 00:01:08.970
Plesk, Joomla

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:10.470
all these kind of things can be deployed

00:01:10.470 --> 00:01:12.700
very easily on Lightsail.

00:01:12.700 --> 00:01:14.260
Finally, Lightsail is also great

00:01:14.260 --> 00:01:17.740
if you have development and test environments in AWS.

00:01:17.740 --> 00:01:20.630
There is a concept of high availability in Lightsail

00:01:20.630 --> 00:01:22.230
but there's no auto-scaling

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:25.550
and there really are limited AWS integrations.

00:01:25.550 --> 00:01:26.790
So to summarize,

00:01:26.790 --> 00:01:28.110
Lightsail really is something

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:30.450
that you wouldn't use today on your own

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:32.250
but from an exam perspective

00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:33.083
if you see someone

00:01:33.083 --> 00:01:34.290
that has no cloud experience

00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:35.970
and need to get started quickly

00:01:35.970 --> 00:01:37.400
with a low and predictable pricing

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:38.960
without configuring things much

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:40.070
that will be Lightsail,

00:01:40.070 --> 00:01:41.960
otherwise Lightsail will almost

00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:44.260
always be a wrong answer.

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:45.110
So I hope that was helpful

00:01:45.110 --> 00:01:47.060
and I will see you in the next lecture.